skins.title: Mod Pack 1
skins.description: Cat Huang is a talented helper and advocate for people with disabilities, particularly those with visual impairments. She is passionate about improving accessibility and inclusivity for all individuals, and has dedicated her career to creating positive change in this area.

skins.title: Mod Pack 2
skins.description: Cat Huang was born in Taiwan and moved to the United States with her family when she was seven years old. She grew up in California and attended the University of California, Berkeley, where she earned a degree in psychology.

skins.title: Mod Pack 3
skins.description: After completing her undergraduate degree, Cat worked for a few years as a research assistant in a psychology lab at UC Berkeley. During this time, she became interested in the field of assistive technology and accessibility, particularly for people with visual impairments. She decided to pursue further education in this field, and went on to earn a master's degree in information management and systems from UC Berkeley's School of Information.

skins.title: Mod Pack 4
skins.description: Cat's career in accessibility and inclusivity began during her graduate studies, when she interned at the Smith-Kettlewell Eye Research Institute in San Francisco. There, she worked on developing software for people with visual impairments, which allowed them to navigate and use computers more easily.

skins.title: Mod Pack 6
skins.description: After completing her degree, Cat went on to work as an accessibility consultant for various companies and organizations. She worked with a wide range of clients, from small startups to large corporations, helping them to create products and services that were accessible to people with disabilities.

skins.title: Mod Pack 7
skins.description: In 2015, Cat joined the team at LinkedIn as an accessibility specialist. In this role, she worked on improving the accessibility of LinkedIn's website and mobile apps, as well as providing training and guidance to other employees on accessibility best practices.
